inauthenticity, bad research.

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:53.140
I have been guilty
of both in my career.

00:49:53.140 --> 00:49:55.640
But for a book such as

00:49:55.640 --> 00:50:01.190
"The Sandcastle Girls,"
research was critical.

00:50:01.190 --> 00:50:08.230 position:56%
Which is why so many times, over the
last few years, I've been traveling

00:50:08.230 --> 00:50:10.920
to the Middle East to
Armenia, to Turkey.

00:50:10.920 --> 00:50:15.170
And all of the photographs
I'm about to show you, I took,

00:50:15.170 --> 00:50:16.790
except for this first one.

00:50:16.790 --> 00:50:20.320
This first one was taken by
my wife, Victoria Blewer,

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:21.660
who is a fine art photographer.

00:50:21.660 --> 00:50:25.900
And it's infinitely better than
anything else you're going to see.

00:50:25.900 --> 00:50:31.840
But I want to share these
photos of Anatolia with you.

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:38.810
Among the echoes that reverberates
with me always, is Kayseri.

00:50:38.810 --> 00:50:44.150
Because of course, that is
where the Bohjalian's are from.

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:49.870
Outside of Istanbul,
there are, I believe,

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:57.390
no more than four structurally
intact Armenian churches.

00:50:57.390 --> 00:51:03.340
There is the tiny, beautiful little
church on Musa Dagh, for the 200

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:05.540
or so Armenians in that community.

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:09.800
All decedents of the survivors
of Musa Dagh, who returned.

00:51:09.800 --> 00:51:14.200 position:56%
But that is the only active
Armenian church congregation outside

00:51:14.200 --> 00:51:15.500
of Istanbul.

00:51:15.500 --> 00:51:16.800
That's one.

00:51:16.800 --> 00:51:23.210
There's Akdamar, restored as
a museum of sorts on Lake Von.

00:51:23.210 --> 00:51:29.800
There's [inaudible], restored
by the Kurdish municipality.

00:51:29.800 --> 00:51:33.610
And there's this one on the screen,

00:51:33.610 --> 00:51:40.680
Saint Gregory in Kayseri,
behind barbed wire.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:42.780
On Akdamar, Saint Gregory
[inaudible],

00:51:42.780 --> 00:51:47.770
there's no Armenian
congregation there every week.

00:51:47.770 --> 00:51:49.090
But the structures remain.

00:51:49.090 --> 00:51:55.340
And so, it was important to
go stand inside this church.

00:51:55.340 --> 00:51:58.000
The Kurdish caretaker brought us

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:01.620
through the barbed
wire and let us in.

00:52:01.620 --> 00:52:06.770
And as I was standing there
and whispering, moved,

00:52:06.770 --> 00:52:12.190
my wife said to me,
you realize, don't you,

00:52:12.190 --> 00:52:15.370
that this is where your
grandfather was baptized.

00:52:15.370 --> 00:52:18.820
You're now breathing the
air that he breathed.

00:52:18.820 --> 00:52:24.280
And whenever I see this image,
I hear not merely the echo

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:32.590
of my wife's voice, but I hear the
echo of that baptism in the 1890's.

00:52:32.590 --> 00:52:35.730
Most Armenian churches
and monasteries

00:52:35.730 --> 00:52:38.660
in Anatolia are not
structurally intact.

00:52:38.660 --> 00:52:41.550
Most of them are relics.

00:52:41.550 --> 00:52:48.020
They are places such as
[inaudible], also on Lake Von.

00:52:48.020 --> 00:52:52.490
Once the home to our reverend
fathers, now the home to graffiti

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:57.700
and seagulls, [inaudible],
ransacked regularly for gold

00:52:57.700 --> 00:53:00.840
that probably never was there.

00:53:00.840 --> 00:53:07.380
This is the cradle, in some
ways, of Armenian civilization.

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:08.680
This is [inaudible].

00:53:08.680 --> 00:53:12.820
This is what it looked
like circa 1910.

00:53:12.820 --> 00:53:15.330
This is what remains today.

00:53:16.400 --> 00:53:20.560
Saint Bartholomew on
the Iranian border.

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:24.510
I must have 75 images
like this on my phone.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:27.490
I want to show you
just one more, though.

00:53:27.490 --> 00:53:29.460
Saint Sarkis.

00:53:29.460 --> 00:53:34.180
Whenever I show this image,
Armenians who have been to Ani,

00:53:34.180 --> 00:53:38.230
which is in Northeastern
Turkey at the Armenian border,

00:53:38.230 --> 00:53:40.470
most people presume it is Ani.

00:53:40.470 --> 00:53:42.810
It's actually not, but
it is very near Ani.

00:53:42.810 --> 00:53:49.000
Ani, the city of a thousand
churches in the Middle Ages.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:50.570
But I share with you Saint Sarkis

00:53:50.570 --> 00:53:54.890
because I took this
photograph in 2015.

00:53:54.890 --> 00:54:00.820
If I had been standing on the
cliff, looking down at it in 1950,

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:08.350 position:56%
you would have seen five
completely intact church structures,

00:54:08.350 --> 00:54:09.740
all a part of this complex.

00:54:09.740 --> 00:54:12.680 position:56%
And today, this is all that remains.

00:54:12.680 --> 00:54:17.360
Why? Because in the mid 1950's,
the five-church complex was used

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:22.130
for artillery target
practice, medieval churches.

00:54:22.130 --> 00:54:30.390
Now, the Middle East and Anatolia,
are awash in unmarked masquerades.

00:54:30.390 --> 00:54:32.270
Which I will share
with you, but one.

00:54:32.270 --> 00:54:34.960
This is the Dudan crevasse.

00:54:34.960 --> 00:54:38.090
And here's what the history
books said happened here

00:54:38.090 --> 00:54:42.350
over a three-day period in 1915.

00:54:42.350 --> 00:54:46.060
The 10,000 members of the
Armenian community were marched

00:54:46.060 --> 00:54:47.930
to the edge of the cliff.

00:54:47.930 --> 00:54:51.750
And every single one of them
was shot, stabbed or bayonetted.

00:54:51.750 --> 00:54:54.220
Their bodies thrown
unceremoniously to the crevasse

00:54:54.220 --> 00:54:57.600
at the bottom of the gorge.

00:54:57.600 --> 00:55:00.410
The first time I went
here was in 2013.

00:55:00.410 --> 00:55:04.410
And as I am always
when I go to Anatolia,

00:55:04.410 --> 00:55:08.080
I was with my great
friend Khatchig Mouradian.

00:55:08.080 --> 00:55:10.490
There are five other
Armenian Americans.

00:55:10.490 --> 00:55:16.570 position:56%
And the seven of us, after listening
to the echoes at the Dudan crevasse,

00:55:16.570 --> 00:55:20.110
went to Chunkush to see the
remains of the Armenian church

00:55:20.110 --> 00:55:22.710
and the Armenian monastery there.

00:55:22.710 --> 00:55:25.460
And as we were leaving,
a Kurdish gentleman,

00:55:25.460 --> 00:55:27.320
my age, knocked on or van door.

00:55:27.320 --> 00:55:30.610
And begged us not to leave.

00:55:30.610 --> 00:55:34.220
He said, please, you must
meet my mother-in-law.

00:55:34.220 --> 00:55:36.270
She's 98 years old.

00:55:36.270 --> 00:55:39.820
And we all did the
math in our heads.

00:55:39.820 --> 00:55:43.310
His mother-in-law was born in 1915.

00:55:43.310 --> 00:55:45.490
And so, we went to meet her.

00:55:45.490 --> 00:55:47.680
And thank goodness, we did.

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:51.670
Because in this case, the
history books were wrong.

00:55:51.670 --> 00:55:57.260
Not every Armenian was killed
that cataclysmic three-day period.

00:55:57.260 --> 00:56:01.700
There's one young Armenian woman
in the line who was so beautiful.

00:56:01.700 --> 00:56:04.380
That a member of the
Kurdish killing party,

00:56:04.380 --> 00:56:08.790
pulled her from the
line and married her.

00:56:08.790 --> 00:56:14.680
She had in her arms her
newborn baby, an infant.

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:20.730
And that is who we met
that day in 2013, Asiya,

00:56:20.730 --> 00:56:25.870
the last living Armenian
in Chunkush.

00:56:25.870 --> 00:56:30.370
And as Khatchig was getting
her story, with her hand,

00:56:30.370 --> 00:56:34.190
she looked at us and she
said, you're Armenian.

00:56:34.190 --> 00:56:35.690
You're Armenian.

00:56:35.690 --> 00:56:38.460
You're really Armenian.

00:56:38.460 --> 00:56:40.080
And that's when I got it.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:43.370
Her son-in-law was a good
man, a very good man.

00:56:43.370 --> 00:56:49.100
It wasn't that he wanted us to
meet her, he wanted her to meet us.

00:56:49.100 --> 00:56:52.460
To see that while she is
the last living Armenian

00:56:52.460 --> 00:56:56.560
in Chunkush, the race continues.

00:56:56.560 --> 00:56:58.150
We survive.

00:56:58.150 --> 00:57:02.900
Which is why when I return,
I always visit Chunkush.

00:57:02.900 --> 00:57:06.960
And why, when I returned
there in 2014,

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:10.670
I brought my beautiful
daughter and my beautiful wife,

00:57:10.670 --> 00:57:13.410
so that Asiya could
meet Grace Experience.

00:57:13.410 --> 00:57:20.430
And see yet another generation
of Armenians walking the earth.

00:57:20.430 --> 00:57:23.950
Now, I said I was going
to end with Nazaret.

00:57:23.950 --> 00:57:32.740
In 2014, I came across
two-volume encyclopedia.

00:57:32.740 --> 00:57:37.270
The notable Armenians of Kayseri.

00:57:37.270 --> 00:57:41.890
And as I was thumbing through
this two-volume encyclopedia,

00:57:41.890 --> 00:57:47.770
I came across my great
grandfather, Nazaret Bedros.

00:57:47.770 --> 00:57:51.510
There were seven pages
about him in Armenian.

00:57:51.510 --> 00:57:55.610
And I recognized him,
as will you, instantly.

00:57:55.610 --> 00:58:01.210
And for the life of me, I could
not understand why there were seven

00:58:01.210 --> 00:58:05.340
pages about a tailor.

00:58:05.340 --> 00:58:10.940
So, I asked Khatchig, my
Guggenheim, my Godfather.

00:58:10.940 --> 00:58:13.650 position:56%
I said Khatchig, could you translate
this for me and explain to me?

00:58:13.650 --> 00:58:19.220
And he called me up,
after reading it and said,

00:58:19.220 --> 00:58:22.160
your grandfather wasn't a tailor.

00:58:22.160 --> 00:58:26.820
Maybe he dabbled as a
tailor, but he was a writer.

00:58:26.820 --> 00:58:29.240
He was, in fact, a prodigy.

00:58:29.240 --> 00:58:36.590
At the age of 12, he was taken
from Kayseri to perform as far

00:58:36.590 --> 00:58:38.130
as the Southeast as Jerusalem.

00:58:38.130 --> 00:58:40.660
As far as the West
as Constantinople.

00:58:40.660 --> 00:58:47.650
And he didn't just write
his poems, he sang them.

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:50.830
He was a troubadour.

00:58:50.830 --> 00:58:55.770
He was performing across Anatolia
in the 1860's and the 1870's.

00:58:55.770 --> 00:58:58.730
A Bruce Springsteen, of the
Anatolian plains [brief laughter].

00:58:58.730 --> 00:59:03.940
And his poetry, it was upbeat.

00:59:03.940 --> 00:59:05.990
It was ebullient.

00:59:05.990 --> 00:59:12.920
It was an unceasing beautiful
celebration of the Armenians,

00:59:12.920 --> 00:59:16.400
the Turks, the Kurds of Kayseri.

00:59:16.400 --> 00:59:18.230
The landscape.

00:59:18.230 --> 00:59:19.830
The topography.

00:59:19.830 --> 00:59:26.240
Think Walt Whitman, with its
exuberance and enthusiasm

00:59:26.240 --> 00:59:30.760
for the beauty and the
community of Anatolia.

00:59:32.080 --> 00:59:39.950
All that changed at the end of
his life on November 18, 1895.

00:59:39.950 --> 00:59:43.270
Almost a century to the
date, when his great,

00:59:43.270 --> 00:59:46.170
great granddaughter Grace
Experience would be born.

00:59:46.170 --> 00:59:51.160 position:56%
In a runup to the Armenian genocide,
we call the Hamidian Massacres,

00:59:51.160 --> 00:59:57.270
250,000 Armenians died, the
slaughter came to Kayseri.

00:59:57.270 --> 01:00:03.100
And the Bohjalian family
was witness and victim.

01:00:03.100 --> 01:00:06.270
And now, at the very
end of his life,

01:00:06.270 --> 01:00:11.260
despite the fact among his children
was a little boy named Levon.

01:00:11.260 --> 01:00:16.050
He wrote the longest
poem of his life.

01:00:16.050 --> 01:00:22.870
A 70-quatrain epic, chronicling
what he witnessed on November 18.

01:00:22.870 --> 01:00:27.680
I will share with you, but
two of the 70-quatrains.

01:00:27.680 --> 01:00:30.950 position:56%
"They killed infidels with axes,
daggers and didn't ask who you were,

01:00:30.950 --> 01:00:33.050
whether merchant or coolie."

01:00:33.050 --> 01:00:35.630
"They took the babies out of the
wombs of their mothers and those

01:00:35.630 --> 01:00:38.990
who witnessed lost their minds."

01:00:38.990 --> 01:00:40.570
Think [inaudible].

01:00:40.570 --> 01:00:48.230
I have always been so proud
to be my father's son.

01:00:48.230 --> 01:00:54.130
I was always so proud to be
my grandfather's grandson.

01:00:54.130 --> 01:01:00.490
But that's the thing about
identity and about genocide.

01:01:00.490 --> 01:01:03.420
Whenever we talk about genocide,
we always go right to the numbers.

01:01:03.420 --> 01:01:05.920
The six million, the 1.5 million.

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:10.420
But it's not just the
souls that are lost.

01:01:10.420 --> 01:01:12.880
It's the stories.

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:18.980
It's why the work of Levon Avdoyan
and everyone who works with him

01:01:18.980 --> 01:01:23.750
in this wing of the Library
of Congress, are so important.

01:01:23.750 --> 01:01:26.550
Because you collect the stories.

01:01:26.550 --> 01:01:28.600
You preserve the maps.

01:01:28.600 --> 01:01:33.370
You preserve the photographs,
the poetry, the Abovyan.

01:01:33.370 --> 01:01:37.560
You preserve our cultural identity

01:01:37.560 --> 01:01:42.500
against the relentless
tide of assimilation.

01:01:42.500 --> 01:01:46.190
I find it so interesting that
as proud as I've always been

01:01:46.190 --> 01:01:53.820
to be Aaron Bohjalian's son, Levon
Nazareth's grandson, that's in only

01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:58.380
in midlife that I've
discovered how proud I can be

01:01:58.380 --> 01:02:01.500
to be Nazaret Bedrose's
great-grandson.

01:02:01.500 --> 01:02:04.160
Because it is only at
midlife that I've discovered,

01:02:04.160 --> 01:02:08.770
I am not the first
Bohjalian to be a writer

01:02:08.770 --> 01:02:12.170 position:56%
and to plum this part of my history.

01:02:12.170 --> 01:02:15.990
I am humbled to be but the second.

01:02:15.990 --> 01:02:19.510
Thank you so much [speaking
in foreign language]

